\subsection{Rotational Surface Projection}
To test whether the manifold supports constraint tightening through projection, we reused the
phase dial itself as a projection operator. After computing the midpoint $F_{AB}$, we swept
$\alpha$ over $\text{rotate}(F_{AB}, \alpha)$ and found
$\alpha^* = \arg\max_\alpha \max_k \text{score}(\text{rotate}(F_{AB}, \alpha), F_k)$,
the rotation that maximises alignment with the nearest corpus item.

Across all five first-hop angles, the snap consistently selected
$\alpha^* = {{.SnapAlpha | f3}}^{\circ}$ with a corpus peak score of ${{.SnapScore | f4}}$,
and produced a gain of ${{.SnapGain | f4}}$---identical to both the raw midpoint
(\,${{.MidptGain | f4}}$\,) and Baseline~2 (\,${{.Baseline2 | f4}}$\,).
The rotational projection finds the surface maximum, but it is the same maximum that $B$ already
dominates. This confirms that one-dimensional global phase rotation lacks the degrees of freedom
to reach a \textit{different} surface ridge that simultaneously satisfies both constraints.

